Assumptions for Data Type Matching & Analysis Project
1. Data Availability & Access
Complete Data Access: Assumes that all required databases, tables, and data sources (e.g., Snowflake, AWS S3) are fully accessible.
Timely Data Access: Assumes minimal latency when querying or retrieving data from Snowflake or other cloud resources.
No Data Quality Issues: Assumes that data in the system is clean and well-structured (minimal missing or corrupted values).
2. Technical Infrastructure
Cloud Resources: Assumes that sufficient AWS resources (e.g., EC2, S3, Glue) are available to handle data processing workloads.
Python Ecosystem: Assumes that Python and relevant libraries (e.g., Pandas, Snowflake Connector, FuzzyWuzzy) are installed and functional on the AWS EC2 instances.
Generative AI Access: Assumes that access to Generative AI services (e.g., OpenAI, AWS Bedrock) is available and functional for advanced AI tasks.
3. Data Volume & Scale
Moderate Data Volume: Assumes that the data volume is manageable and does not exceed the current capacity of the infrastructure (e.g., Snowflake and EC2).
Data Growth: Assumes gradual growth of data volume, not an exponential increase within the project duration.
4. Matching and Statistical Analysis
Schema Alignment: Assumes that tables across databases have some level of schema alignment, enabling easier data type matching.
Categorical Variables: Assumes that similar columns like "gender" and "sex" are well-categorized and use standard values for the Chi-square tests (e.g., M/F for gender).
Similarity Algorithms: Assumes that Levenshtein, Soundex, and other matching algorithms provide accurate and relevant results within acceptable thresholds.
5. Business and Functional Assumptions
Stakeholder Availability: Assumes regular availability of stakeholders for feedback and project direction alignment.
Business Rule Clarity: Assumes that business rules and objectives (e.g., what constitutes a "match" between columns) are well-defined and documented.
Consistent Reporting Requirements: Assumes that reporting formats, tools (e.g., QuickSight, Tableau), and dashboards will not change drastically during the project.
6. Security & Compliance
Data Security: Assumes that data governance, privacy, and security standards (e.g., GDPR, HIPAA) are already in place and being followed.
Access Control: Assumes that proper role-based access control (RBAC) and permissions are configured for data access within Snowflake and AWS.
